Here is a concise, module-wise breakdown of the course topics, stripped of explanations for quick reference:
Module 1: AI Fundamentals
 * The Big Picture: AI vs. Machine Learning vs. Deep Learning
 * Terminology: Algorithms, Models, Training, and Inference
 * Types of AI: Narrow AI vs. General AI (AGI)
 * Real-world Context: History and current industry impact
 * Capabilities: What AI can realistically do vs. what it cannot
Module 2: Generative AI & LLMs
 * The Core Tech: Large Language Models (LLMs) explained
 * The Process: Tokens, context windows, and "super-powered autocomplete"
 * Model Landscape: Text (GPT/Gemini), Image (Midjourney), and Video
 * Technical Flaws: Hallucinations and factual errors
Module 3: Mastery of Prompt Engineering
 * Prompt Frameworks: Role, Context, Task, and Constraints
 * Techniques: Zero-shot, Few-shot, and Chain-of-Thought prompting
 * Iterative Design: Refining outputs through multi-turn conversation
 * Workplace Automation: Summarization, drafting, and data formatting
Module 4: Practical Workplace Workflows
 * Productivity Hacks: Meeting notes, email management, and brainstorming
 * Data Analysis: Using AI to interpret spreadsheets and trends
 * Tool Selection: Finding the right AI tool for specific department tasks
 * The "Human-in-the-Loop" Model: Reviewing and editing AI output
Module 5: Ethics, Safety & Policy
 * Data Privacy: Handling sensitive company and client information
 * Bias & Fairness: Identifying prejudices in AI results
 * Copyright & Legal: Ownership of AI-generated content
 * Company Policy: Guidelines for responsible internal use
Would you like me to expand on the "Mastery of Prompt Engineering" module with a specific checklist for your team?
